WEEK 7 REPORT – Demand, Revenue & Consistency Analysis

During Week 7, the analysis progressed from performance evaluation to identifying business-critical vendors using demand, revenue, and supply consistency metrics.

On Day 23, demand analysis was performed using total quantity as a proxy. Vendors were categorized into high, medium, and low demand groups. The analysis identified 3 high-demand vendors and 2 vendors with both high demand and high risk, indicating potential operational vulnerability. Demand distribution showed that the majority of vendors fall under the low-demand category.

On Day 24, revenue estimation and contribution analysis were conducted. Vendors were segmented based on revenue generation, and 4 vendors were identified as high revenue but high risk, highlighting financially important yet unstable suppliers. Revenue distribution indicated uneven contribution across vendors.

On Day 25, supply consistency and dependency analysis were performed. A consistency score was calculated to evaluate supply stability. The results showed 4 vendors with high demand but low consistency, and 3 critical dependency vendors, indicating reliance on unstable suppliers. Additionally, top risk vendors were identified using a combined risk metric.

Overall, Week 7 provided key business insights by linking demand, revenue, and consistency, enabling identification of high-impact and high-risk vendors for better decision-making in supply chain management.